## .NET MAUI Theme Detection & Override

**Detect the current system theme:**

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

**Subscribe to real-time theme changes:**

```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI on the main thread
    MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() =>
    {
        // your UI refresh logic here
    });
};
```

**Force a specific theme (user override):**

```csharp
// Lock to dark mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Lock to light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Follow system setting again
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**XAML auto-adapting resources** — use `AppThemeBinding` so styles react automatically:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#000000, Dark=#FFFFFF}" />
```

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` = what the OS reports.
- `UserAppTheme` = your app-level override; set it to `Unspecified` to defer back to the system.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires when the **system** theme changes (not when you set `UserAppTheme`).
- Persist the user's choice (e.g., `Preferences.Set("theme", ...)`) and apply it in `App()` constructor so it survives restarts.
